      <block class="full_text">
        <p>FABULOUS HELL</p>
        <p>By Craig Curtis.</p>
        <p>Alyson, paper, $12.95.</p>
        <p>Soaked in booze, sweat and attitude, Craig Curtis's first novel is a brisk ride straight downhill as its nameless protagonist, given an H.I.V. positive diagnosis in the book's first sentence, relentlessly parties his T-cell count down to the brink of oblivion. This loose series of vignettes, written in rapid-fire prose, provide glimpses into his bleak life as he moves from gay nightclubs in Los Angeles to drug binges, flashing back to memories of childhood incest or a grade-school art class. Other characters tend to lurch in and out of the narrative as ungracefully as the protagonist after his fourth martini, and the boyhood memories -- with their Tang references and ''Bewitched'' worship -- seem tired. What keeps our character, and the book, speeding ahead is his dark and campy outlook. His love of black-and-white film divas, his blithe ''I don't care'' mantra and his love of catty comebacks make his deeply superficial narration entertaining despite the desperate subject matter.</p>
        <p>Christine Muhlke</p>
      </block>
